# Comprehensive Guide to C++ Concepts

## Unit 3a: Basic Objects and Operations

### Basic Objects (Structs)

A `struct` in C++ is a user-defined data type that groups together variables of different data types under a single name. This is useful for organizing data.

```cpp
struct Person {
    std::string name;
    int age;
};
```

### Assignment of Objects

When you have two objects of the same type, you can assign one to the other. This copies the values from one object to another.

```cpp
Person person1 = {"Alice", 30};
Person person2;
person2 = person1; // person2 now has the same name and age as person1
```

### . and -> Operators

The dot (`.`) operator is used to access members of a struct or class through an object or a reference. The arrow (`->`) operator is used to access members through a pointer.

```cpp
Person person = {"Bob", 25};
std::cout << person.name; // Access using .

Person* personPtr = &person;
std::cout << personPtr->name; // Access using ->
```

### Use of getline()

`getline()` is a function that reads a line of text from an input stream. It is often used with `std::cin` or file streams.

```cpp
std::string line;
std::getline(std::cin, line);
```

### Checking an Input Stream for Failure

You can check if an input operation was successful using the `fail()` method of the stream.

```cpp
int number;
std::cin >> number;
if (std::cin.fail()) {
    std::cerr << "Invalid input" << std::endl;
}
```

### Using C++ String Class

The `std::string` class provides a rich set of operations for manipulating strings.

```cpp
std::string str = "Hello";
str += " World"; // Concatenation
std::cout << str.length(); // Length of the string
```

## Unit 3b: Defining Your Own Classes

### Defining Your Own Classes

A class is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines a data structure including data members and member functions.

```cpp
class Car {
public:
    std::string make;
    std::string model;
    int year;

    void display() {
        std::cout << year << " " << make << " " << model << std::endl;
    }
};
```

### public vs. private

Access specifiers control the visibility of class members. `public` members are accessible from anywhere, while `private` members are only accessible within the class.

```cpp
class Car {
private:
    std::string make;
public:
    std::string model;
    int year;
};
```

### Constructors and Destructors

A constructor is called when an object is created, and a destructor is called when an object is destroyed.

```cpp
class Car {
public:
    Car() {
        std::cout << "Car created" << std::endl;
    }
    ~Car() {
        std::cout << "Car destroyed" << std::endl;
    }
};
```

### Defining Member Functions

Member functions can be defined inside or outside the class definition.

```cpp
class Car {
public:
    void start();
};

void Car::start() {
    std::cout << "Engine started" << std::endl;
}
```

### Splitting Your Class into Files

It's common to split class definitions into header files (`.h`) and implementation files (`.cpp`).

**Car.h**
```cpp
class Car {
public:
    void start();
};
```

**Car.cpp**
```cpp
#include "Car.h"
void Car::start() {
    std::cout << "Engine started" << std::endl;
}
```

## Unit 4a: Linked Lists

### Implementing Basic Operations

A linked list is a collection of nodes where each node contains data and a reference to the next node.

```cpp
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
};

class LinkedList {
private:
    Node* head;
public:
    LinkedList() : head(nullptr) {}
    void pushFront(int data);
    void popFront();
};

void LinkedList::pushFront(int data) {
    Node* newNode = new Node{data, head};
    head = newNode;
}

void LinkedList::popFront() {
    if (head) {
        Node* temp = head;
        head = head->next;
        delete temp;
    }
}
```

### Efficiency of Various Operations

- **Push Front**: O(1)
- **Pop Front**: O(1)
- **Push Back**: O(n) without a tail pointer, O(1) with a tail pointer
- **Pop Back**: O(n)

### Pros and Cons Compared to Arrays

- **Pros**: Dynamic size, efficient insertions/deletions at the beginning
- **Cons**: No random access, extra memory for pointers

## Unit 4b: vector<T> and deque<T> Basic Operation

### vector<T>

`std::vector` is a dynamic array that can change size.

```cpp
std::vector<int> vec = {1, 2, 3};
vec.push_back(4); // O(1) amortized
vec.pop_back(); // O(1)
```

### deque<T>

`std::deque` (double-ended queue) supports efficient insertion and deletion at both ends.

```cpp
std::deque<int> dq = {1, 2, 3};
dq.push_front(0); // O(1)
dq.push_back(4); // O(1)
```

### Efficiency of Their Operations

- **vector<T>**:
  - **Push Back**: O(1) amortized
  - **Pop Back**: O(1)
  - **Push Front**: O(n)
  - **Pop Front**: O(n)
- **deque<T>**:
  - **Push Front/Back**: O(1)
  - **Pop Front/Back**: O(1)

## Unit 4c: Doubly Linked Lists

### Doubly Linked Lists

A doubly linked list has nodes that contain data and references to both the next and previous nodes.

```cpp
struct Node {
    int data;
    Node* next;
    Node* prev;
};

class DoublyLinkedList {
private:
    Node* head;
    Node* tail;
public:
    DoublyLinkedList() : head(nullptr), tail(nullptr) {}
    void pushFront(int data);
    void pushBack(int data);
    void popFront();
    void popBack();
};

void DoublyLinkedList::pushFront(int data) {
    Node* newNode = new Node{data, head, nullptr};
    if (head) head->prev = newNode;
    head = newNode;
    if (!tail) tail = head;
}

void DoublyLinkedList::pushBack(int data) {
    Node* newNode = new Node{data, nullptr, tail};
    if (tail) tail->next = newNode;
    tail = newNode;
    if (!head) head = tail;
}

void DoublyLinkedList::popFront() {
    if (head) {
        Node* temp = head;
        head = head->next;
        if (head) head->prev = nullptr;
        else tail = nullptr;
        delete temp;
    }
}

void DoublyLinkedList::popBack() {
    if (tail) {
        Node* temp = tail;
        tail = tail->prev;
        if (tail) tail->next = nullptr;
        else head = nullptr;
        delete temp;
    }
}
```

### Efficiency of Various Operations

- **Push Front/Back**: O(1)
- **Pop Front/Back**: O(1)

## Unit 4d: Multidimensional Arrays

### Memory Layout of a Multidimensional Array

Multidimensional arrays are stored in row-major order in C++.

```cpp
int arr[2][3] = {{1, 2, 3}, {4, 5, 6}};
```

### Passing Multidimensional Arrays to Functions

When passing multidimensional arrays to functions, you must specify the size of all dimensions except the first.

```cpp
void printArray(int arr[][3], int rows) {
    for (int i = 0; i < rows; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; ++j) {
            std::cout << arr[i][j] << " ";
        }
        std::cout << std::endl;
    }
}
```

## Unit 4e: Syntax and Use

### Advantages of Passing by Reference

Passing by reference allows a function to modify the actual argument and avoids copying large data structures.

```cpp
void increment(int& value) {
    ++value;
}

int main() {
    int num = 5;
    increment(num);
    std::cout << num; // Outputs 6
}
```

### const References

A `const` reference ensures that the function does not modify the referenced object.

```cpp
void print(const std::string& str) {
    std::cout << str;
}
```

## Unit 4f: File I/O and Error Handling

### Checking for Failure When Opening a File

When opening a file, you should check if the operation was successful.

```cpp
std::ifstream file("example.txt");
if (!file) {
    std::cerr << "Failed to open file" << std::endl;
}
```

### Using C++ ifstream and ofstream Classes for File I/O

`std::ifstream` is used for reading files, and `std::ofstream` is used for writing files.

```cpp
std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt");
std::ofstream outputFile("output.txt");

if (inputFile) {
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(inputFile, line)) {
        outputFile << line << std::endl;
    }
}
```

### Checking for Failure When Attempting to Receive Input

When reading from a stream, you should check if the operation was successful.

```cpp
int number;
inputFile >> number;
if (inputFile.fail()) {
    std::cerr << "Failed to read number" << std::endl;
}
```

This comprehensive guide covers the essential concepts and operations in C++, providing detailed explanations and examples for each topic. Understanding these concepts will enable you to write efficient and robust C++ programs.

